<HL>
   International:
   European Firms Study
   Joint Steel Venture
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   B.ARB B.COS EUROP B.SGL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- Arbed S.A. of Luxembourg and Cockerill Sambre
S.A. of Belgium said they are discussing a 50-50 joint
venture to combine their production and sales of flatsteel
products.
   The share prices of both companies surged about 10% after
the talks were disclosed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We are seeking a European dimension comparable to that of
British Steel, Usinor-Sacilor and Thyssen," a spokesman for
Cockerill Sambre said. The two companies said bigger scale is
necessary to "assure the future of these activities in terms
of applied research, new technologies and investments."
   The joint venture would have annual sales of around 130
billion Belgian francs ($3.96 billion), about half from each
company. Both companies derive around a third of their sales
from flat-steel products. The two said they would retain
their separate identities and pursue their other activities
independently.
   Within three months, the two companies aim to reach a
preliminary conclusion on whether to pursue the proposed
joint venure.
   Cockerill Sambre is about 85%-owned by Belgium's Walloon
regional government. The Luxembourg government owns about 31%
of the voting rights in Arbed, and Societe Generale de
Belgique S.A. owns 25.5%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900809-0108
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900809-0108.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Corn Caper:
   Did North Korea
   Seek U.S. Shipment?
   ---
   Rumor in Grain-Trading Pits
   Says Buyer Got Spooked
   When Word Leaked Out
   ----
   By Scott Kilman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Did North Korea try to buy U.S. corn?
   That's the summer's most intriguing tidbit in the
grain-trading pits here, where brokers use a simple strategy:
buy on rumor, sell on fact.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Many rumors never pan out. But this time the details,
sketchy as they are, are enough to have grain exporters
worrying privately that one of them might have unknowingly
broken the law by helping the hard-line Communist government.
   "It is strictly taboo," said an official of one major
grain firm. U.S. firms are banned from doing business with
North Korea by the Trading With the Enemy Act. In recent
years, transgressions have been on the mundane side,
involving travel agents and tour operators arranging trips to
three other countries on the enemies list: Vietnam, Cambodia
and Cuba.
   Grain, however, is a political powder keg.
   Washington got upset in the 1970s when U.S. grain
merchants quietly sold large amounts of crops to the Soviet
Union. Amid soaring food prices in the U.S., Congress
required grain exporters to disclose their sales to the
government.
   "This one might have fallen through the cracks," said an
export expert at the Agriculture Department, which tracks
overseas grain sales.
   A spokesman at the Treasury Department, which enforces the
trading ban, said it is aware of the North Korean report but
hasn't any evidence of a misdeed. The department can grant a
license to ship goods but usually it does so only for
humanitarian purposes.
   Policing the grain trade is difficult. The origin of a
shipment such as corn can easily be lost as it changes hands.
And attractive deals can pop up in the most unlikely places.
For example, several U.S. grain merchants have received
overtures to buy rice from Vietnam, which has had an usually
large harvest.
   Here's the North Korea rumor: Because that country can't
openly buy corn from the U.S., a Singapore dealer is thought
to have acted as the middleman to arrange shipment. While the
corn was en route, however, word about it started to pop up
in the West. The North Korean government, perhaps anxious
about how it might look for it to need corn from the U.S.,
got spooked and scrapped the deal, the story goes.
   Traders believe that North Korea eventually got the corn
it needed from China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900809-0107
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900809-0107.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Bulletin:
   A Special Background Report
   On Trends in Industry
   And Finance
   ----
   By Pamela Sebastian
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   CCI XON
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<LP>
   THE SAVINGS RATE may shrink further as oil crisis forces
spending changes.
   "Disruption means less income, and less income means less
saving," says Franco Modigliani, the Nobel-laureate economist
at MIT. Savings are crucial to help finance a "dis-saving"
government, and to provide business capital. An oil-price
rise of 6% or 7% won't have much effect, Mr. Modigliani says,
noting: "I would begin to worry at 30%." Harvard economist
Lawrence Summers says even the price hikes so far mean
"you're likely to see some reduction in the savings rate over
the next several quarters." But he adds that "in the long run
it's not likely to have a big effect." Personal savings have
been meager for a while.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   WEFA Group's Larry Kimbell recalls that in the two earlier
oil shocks, about 50% of marginal gains in disposable income
went for energy needs. MIT's Mr. Modigliani says saving is
off world-wide, due to big government deficits and slowing
global economies. He notes some demographics also hurt: Women
swell the work force but add less to savings than to overall
income because of expenses for child care, home help and
prepared food. The oil crisis tops off a tankful of economic
woes, but Jesup Josephthal's David Bostian sees a possible
benefit: "motivation to save more, if the cash drain isn't
overwhelming."
   The 1989 savings rate recently was revised downward by
nearly one percentage point to 4.6%.
                                                                                                       

   SICK OF THE '60s? Too bad. Retailers hope retro rags will
dress up fall profits.
   After heavy discounting in women's apparel last year,
stores aim for firmer margins with reborn miniskirts,
stretch-pants, bodysuits (a.k.a. catsuits), psychedelic
leggings, "tent" dresses and little A-line Jackie ensembles.
In the first half, women's and children's clothing sales
inched up 0.7% to $96.8 billion in real dollars, pressuring
profits, says Edward Johnson, of Johnson Redbook Service. He
adds, "Fashion doesn't make as much difference as the price."
   Kal Ruttenstein, head of fashion direction at
Bloomingdale's, stresses updates, like the new Puccis. Groovy
in the '60s, the Sequel Decade's version has subtle changes
-- a modern shoulder, different darts. Joan Kaner, New York
fashion director at Neiman-Marcus, says of the '60s: "The
clothes were very futuristic. I think we gave it up all too
quickly." Will "go-go" go over again with over-40 women who
now have kids, careers and cellulite? "They might be in
better shape now than in their 20s," says Ms. Kaner. If not,
she notes there are options such as the short but full,
leg-flattering tent dress. She adds: "What's under the tent
is your secret."
                                                                                                       

   ROAD WORRIERS flood auto clubs with gas complaints. But
few cancel vacations.
   The American Automobile Association says members irate
over prices keep phone lines busy. But it says part of the
reason summer trips aren't being canceled is that gas still
accounts for only a small portion of expenses. It figures a
family of four spends about $172 a day for lodging and about
$30 on gas -- up from $20 before the recent increases.
Another reason: Summer is two-thirds over and so are most
vacations.
   Last summer, motorists drove their vehicles on 264 million
trips of 100 miles or more. Meanwhile, membership in major
auto clubs rises. Shell Motor Club says its ranks swell 15% a
year. Requests for help also rise. Amoco Motor Club says
calls for road service rose 3.5% last year while 5.5% more
motorists sought help mapping trips.
   Timely samaritans: 350 California Unocal stations offer
free freeway aid. Vans cruise with cellular phones, gas.
                                                                                                       

   PARTNER WANTED: Nearly 20% of 250 midsize firms polled for
Grant Thornton say their growth strategy calls for a joint
venture. Some 81% say they'd seek a foreign partner; 72%
specify Japanese.
                                                                                                       

   CHARGE IT TO EGOTISM: Citibank tests a credit card with
the owner's photo. The bank hopes the card will thwart theft
and appeal to consumer vanity.
                                                                                                       

   ADOPT-A-BEACH, a cleanup program of the Texas General Land
Office, seeks a hand from plastics firms. Exxon Chemical pays
to convert 5,000 pounds of Texas trash into 12 plastic,
barnacle-proof benches.
                                                                                                       

   HEALTHY BANKS HARRUMPH at being tarred with the troubled
S&amp;L brush.
   An advance promo for a recent ABC-TV "Nightline" episode
about failing banks and thrifts pictured Key Bank of Western
New York in Buffalo. That evening, host Ted Koppel apologized
for "scaring the daylights out of depositors." The gaffe
footage related to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.'s
earlier closing of Permanent Bank for Savings and its
subsequent purchase by KeyCorp. Healthy KeyCorp units were
deluged with calls and some withdrawals.
   During the program, Stanford economist Dan Brumbaugh got
things roiling again by calling most of the nation's 10
largest banks "near true insolvency." Several incensed big
banks said that a few customers, citing the remarks, withdrew
all their funds the next morning. McKinsey &amp; Co.'s Lowell
Bryan calls the economist's comments "unhelpful" and
"inaccurate." Oh, yeah? Mr. Brumbaugh replies the comments
are "helpful" and "accurate."
   Overall, banks benefit from S&amp;L woes. In 1989, small
deposits rose 17% at banks despite moderating rates.
                                                                                                       

   BRIEFS: Dead Stop, a chemical patch that detects carbon
monoxide in cars, buses and basements, comes from CO Alert
Inc., Fort Lauderdale, Fla. . . . A College of Wooster
student thesis carries this note of thanks: "to Rene for
proffreading."
</TEXT>
