<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                          MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts -- $600 million of 7 1/8% general obligation
bond anticipation notes due Oct. 17, priced by a Goldman
Sachs &amp; Co. group to yield 5.85%. The bonds are rated
MIG-1/SP-1-Plus.
   New York City Municipal Water Authority -- $285 million of
water and sewer system revenue bonds, priced by a Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. group. The 1991 Series A bonds
were priced to yield from 6.20% in 1991 to 7.70% in 2019.
Serial bond yields range from 6.20% in 1991 to 7.50% in 2005.
Zero-coupon capital appreciation bonds due in 2006-10 yield
7.25%. The issue has been rated single-A/single-A-minus.
There are $76.8 million of 7.25% term bonds priced to yield
7.40% in 2015, $88.9 million of 7 1/2% term bonds priced to
yield 7.70% in 2019 and $69.1 million of 6% term bonds priced
to yield 7.55% in 2020.
   Port Authority of New York and New Jersey -- $100 million
of consolidated bonds, 70th Series, via a Prudential-Bache
Capital Funding group. The bonds were priced to yield from
7.10% in 2005 to 7.40% in 2025. The issue is rated
single-A-1/double-A-minus. Term bonds have a 7 1/4% coupon
and are priced to yield 7.40% in 2025.
                                                                                                       

                          MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $500.2 million of
Remic mortgage securities offered in 19 classes by Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. The offering, Series 1990-109, is backed by
Fannie Mae 9 1/2 securities. Price and yield data weren't
immediately available.
   Collateralized Mortgage Obligation Trust 63 -- $500
million of Remic mortgage securities offered in nine classes
by Salomon Brothers Inc. The offering is backed by Government
National Mortgage Association securities with a weighted
average coupon rate of 9% and weighted average remaining term
to maturity of 26.33 years. Among classes for which details
were available, planned yield spreads on the 9% coupon issue
ranged from 60 basis points above three-year Treasury notes
to 130 basis points above 10-year Treasurys. There is an
optional redemption at par when 5% of the bonds remain
outstanding.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities offered in 14 classes by Citicorp.
The offering, Series 1990-110, is backed by Fannie Mae 9%
securities. Price and yield data weren't immediately
available.
                                                                                                       

                        ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Discover Card Trust -- $500 million of 1990C Class A
credit card pass-through certificates offered with a coupon
rate of 8.75% at 99.765 to yield 8.87% through Dean Witter
Reynolds. The securities yield 70 basis points over the
Treasury's three-year note. The offering has an average life
of 36.5 months and an expected final maturity of 42 months.
The legal maturity is 5 1/2 years. The underlying credit-card
receivables were sold by Discover Receivables Financing
Corp., a unit of Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. and serviced by
Delaware-based Greenwood Trust Co. The securities are
expected to be rated triple-A by Moody's Investors Service
and Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. based on the quality of the
underlying loans and a subordinated class now totaling about
10% of the senior securities.
   Southeast Bank Credit Card Trust -- $160 million 1990-B
issue of securities backed by credit card receivables,
offered with a coupon rate of 8.60% at 99 21/32 to yield
8.762% through Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. The securities yield 75
basis points more than two-year Treasury notes. A triple-A
rating is expected from Moody's and S&amp;P based on the quality
of the underlying credit card loans and a letter of credit
from Credit Suisse covering 13% of the deal. The seller and
servicer of the underlying loans is Southeast Bank. Expected
final maturity is Jan. 15, 1993, and stated final maturity is
Nov. 15, 1994.
                                                                                                       

                           AGENCY
                                                                                                       

   Federal Farm Credit Banks -- $275 million of bonds due
Sept. 5, 1995, priced at par for an initial yield of 8.74%.
The bonds, which are noncallable for two years, will be
reoffered at various prices. The bonds were priced at a
spread of 31 basis points above the Treasury's five-year note
through underwriters Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
                                                                                                       

