<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Episcopalians Happily
   Avoiding Extinction
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<LP>
   Let us hope your readers got past the eye-catching but
irrelevant headline on Wade Clark Roof's July 20
editorial-page article highlighting some trends in U.S.
religion -- "The Episcopalian Goes the Way of the Dodo." The
headline was not only misleading but, happy to say,
erroneous.
   Those interested in statistics might reflect on the
following: There are about 2.5 million Episcopalians in the
U.S., in 7,500 congregations (a number that has stayed fairly
constant), with 8,200 full-time priests in 100 dioceses. Far
from extinct, wouldn't you say? And, Sunday attendance is up
24.7% since 1974 in Episcopal churches, which have the
highest per capita of giving of all the mainline churches.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It's also interesting to note that George Gallup, whose
data was cited in the table accompanying the article, said in
an overview of a recent study done by the Gallup Organization
of "The Spiritual Health of the Episcopal Church," that the
church is "substantially orthodox . . . committed to growth .
. . open to change . . . and {wanting more involvement in}
ecology, matters of justice, war and peace."
   Headline aside, thanks for running the article and for the
challenge it contains for all of the churches, to quote: "The
religiously non-affiliated have grown to 9% today from 2% in
the early 1950s. . . . Many within this group have dropped
out from the mainline Protestant and Catholic churches. . .
."
   This time, as we approach the millennium, is the Decade of
Evangelism for the Anglican Communion, the Roman Catholic
Church, and others as well. We have a saving message to
share. Let us get beyond the numbers game and our concerns
about "how we are doing" as institutions and share the Good
News in word and deed.
   The Rev. A. Wayne Schwab
   Evangelism Officer
   The Episcopal Church
   New York
   ---
   Regarding Yale President Ezra Stiles's erroneous
prediction in 1783 that a future America would be "divided
about equally among Congregationalists, Presbyterians and
Episcopalians," Thomas Jefferson's crystal ball was even more
clouded.
   Writing to a friend in 1822, Jefferson said, "I rejoice
that in this blessed country of free inquiry and belief,
which has surrendered its creed and conscience to neither
kings nor priests, the genuine doctrine of only one God is
reviving, and I trust that there is not a young man now
living in these United States who will not die as Unitarian."
   Lyda Smayling
   Minneapolis
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900809-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900809-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   A Taxpayer's Outrage
   Must Be Seen in Context
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   With regard to "Folklore and Furnace: A Tale of Two NEA
Grantees," Leisure &amp; Arts, July 24, I had two reactions.
   The first is that being a large employer in an area is a
strange justification for an arts grant. Perhaps Appalshop
Roadside Theater, with an annual budget of $1.6 million and
37 employees, might just as appropriately qualify for
assistance under state or federal small-business assistance
programs, but it might have to meet some minimum criteria
that NEA recipients don't have to meet -- like being
self-supporting after having received subsidies for 20 years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The second reaction is that I am glad Franklin Furnace
Archives Inc. was able to raise $17,000 from willing
contributors. Surely it is better for society overall that
contributions to the arts be voluntary rather than coerced. I
find it disturbing that it is considered a fair exchange that
money I have worked to earn and pay taxes with is considered
well spent if it pays someone to smear chocolate syrup on
herself in public. And I am baffled that while I can go to
jail for not paying my federal income taxes, someone gets
tax-free money from the government to behave in ways that I
attempt to prohibit my six-year-old from doing in his own
home. (His actions, just as Karen Finley's, also must be seen
in context to be understood.)
   The issue is not obscenity -- the issue is that the
federal government (or any government) should spend tax money
on things that are at least as important and serious to
society as a whole as the efforts the government expends in
raising funds to pay for such expenditures.
   Diane L. Warriner
   Camp Hill, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
