<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   PHILLIPS PETROLEUM CUT its wholesale gasoline price by 4.5
cents a gallon, and Arco froze prices for a week. The firms
acted amid an outcry over alleged gouging by oil firms and
after Bush asked the industry to "show restraint." Crude
prices, meanwhile, sank as much as $3 a barrel on news that
Saudi Arabia and others are prepared to boost output. But
such production increases are unlikely to fully offset the
loss of supplies from Iraq and Kuwait.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Frank Lorenzo will sell most of his stake in Continental
Airlines to SAS and will step down as chairman and chief
executive, according to people familiar with his plans. Delta
Air President Hollis Harris is expected to succeed Lorenzo as
chief executive.
   ---
   The stock market rallied on falling oil prices. The Dow
Jones industrials rose 24.26 points. The Mideast turmoil
disrupted the Treasury's quarterly securities auction, but
kept the dollar firm against most currencies. Tokyo stocks
rebounded sharply Wednesday.
   ---
   American Airlines, Midway and America West each announced
a 10% fare rise to offset higher fuel costs.
   ---
   Sears's chairman reassumed the reins of the company's
giant merchandising operation in what amounts to an admission
that the firm's retailing approach isn't working.
   ---
   The economy was slowing markedly even before oil prices
shot up, the Fed reported. The East and parts of the Midwest
were especially weak.
   The survey adds to evidence that a recession is near, if
not yet here.
   ---
   The FDIC is expected next week to consider raising the
premiums paid by banks to insure their deposits.
   ---
   Money-market fund assets soared $6.8 billion in the past
week, much of it moved from stock and bond funds, as
investors sought refuge from the fallout of the Mideast
crisis.
   ---
   A UAL union group won a 60-day extension of the financing
deadline for a proposed buy-out of the company.
   ---
   A strike at a GM parts plant could force shutdowns at
eight car and truck assembly sites within two days. The
immediate impact demonstrates the Big Three's vulnerability
as a Sept. 14 national strike deadline nears.
   ---
   Eastern Europe could suffer a devastating blow from higher
energy prices caused by the Mideast crisis. In the West, the
EC also now expects slower growth and higher inflation.
   ---
   KPMG Peat Marwick's Larry Horner won't seek re-election as
chairman and chief executive of the consulting and accounting
firm.
   ---
   Volkswagen is offering a money-back guarantee, for three
months or 3,000 miles, on one of its models.
   ---
   Pacific Enterprises posted a $229 million second-quarter
loss after taking $275 million in write-downs on its oil and
retailing operations. The firm disclosed that its retailing
chief quit and said it may close 10% of its stores.
   ---
   A Bear Stearns broker was suspended for at least two years
for his alleged role in an insider-trading case involving LTV
Corp.'s former chairman.
   ---
   Chemical Banking created a six-member office of the
chairman to run the parent and its main bank units.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 190,400,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2734.90, up 24.26; transportation 991.42, up 26.64; utilities
205.55, up 1.14.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3360.47, off
1.47.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.45, off 0.09;
spot index 131.71, off 0.61.
   Dollar: 149.80 yen, off 1.15; 1.5925 marks, up 0.0050.
</TEXT>
