<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH OPENED the economic summit amid differences over aid
for the Soviets.
   The U.S., West Germany and Japan agreed to diverge on the
issue of providing aid to Moscow and Beijing, but the leaders
of the largest industrial nations were seeking agreement on
several other difficult issues at the 16th annual economic
summit in Houston. The U.S. has accepted that Bonn is going
ahead with providing assistance to the Kremlin, and that
Japan is planning to resume lending to China. But the U.S.
aggressively pressed European nations to reduce their
trade-distorting subsidies for many agricultural goods.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff Sununu said Bush understands
that the summit partners will take a variety of approaches on
trade issues because of their "different sets of priorities."
   ---
   GORBACHEV WON approval for redesigning the Communist
Party's Politburo.
   Advancing the Soviet president's campaign to maintain
control of the party while restructuring its leadership,
delegates to a party congress voted by a large margin to back
his proposal for bringing the party chiefs from the 15
republics into an enlarged Politburo. The new lineup means
that more moderates will be included in the policymaking
body, and that the restive republics will be given expanded
powers. The revised membership rules also will erode the
traditional domination of the Politburo by the Russian
hard-liners.
   Soviet miners said they would stage a one-day protest
strike tomorrow despite an appeal for labor peace from
Gorbachev and other government officials.
   ---
   A group of 51 Albanian refugees arrived in Czechoslovakia,
and a U.N. envoy was attempting to negotiate safe passage for
more than 5,000 other asylum-seekers who have taken refuge in
Western embassies in Albania's capital, Tirana. The Albanians
stormed the embassies in hopes of fleeing from the hard-line
Communist regime.
   ---
   NASA officials said they haven't pinpointed the mysterious
hydrogen leak that grounded the space shuttle fleet, even
though engineers reproduced the leak in lab tests. The
engineers detected escaping hydrogen in a test of hardware
from the shuttle Columbia, but the agency said it doesn't
know which part of the system is leaking.
   ---
   New York has been selected by Democratic National
Committee Chairman Ronald Brown to host the party's 1992
national convention, sources said. Brown told aides he had
picked New York over New Orleans. He is likely to notify
mayors of the two cities today and is slated to make his
choice public at a news conference tomorrow.
   ---
   Street fighting broke out in Managua between supporters of
Nicaraguan President Chamorro and striking pro-Sandinista
workers, killing at least one man and wounding 34 other
people. According to leaders of the strike, more than 100,000
workers are taking part in the nationwide walkout.
   ---
   Shamir's month-old government passed its first survival
test by defeating no-confidence motions in the Israeli
parliament. The motions accused the prime minister of failing
to provide enough housing amid an influx of Soviet Jewish
immigrants, and also challenged his plans to let Jewish
settlers operate a civil guard in occupied lands.
   ---
   Mandela was welcomed at the opening of the annual summit
of the Organization of African Unity in Addis Ababa.
Ethiopian leader Mengistu said Pretoria's release of the
black leader had encouraged the OAU to step up its fight
against apartheid, but added that recent actions by South
African President de Klerk weren't enough.
   ---
   An anti-apartheid leader quit his church posts in South
Africa following reports that he was having an affair with a
television star. Allan Boesak told his Calvinist congregation
that he did nothing wrong but still had to resign. The
mixed-race minister had risen from farm laborer to become
head of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   ---
   A Los Angeles jury began deliberations in Raymond Buckey's
second molestation trial involving the defunct McMartin
PreSchool in California. Buckey, 32, who is being tried on
eight counts, testified that he never molested children at
the school owned by his family. He was acquitted of 40 counts
in the first trial, which ended in January.
   ---
   Anti-government violence spread across Kenya and police
were told to use whatever force necessary to quell the
protests. Five people were reported killed, bringing the
three-day death toll to eight. The government condemned the
U.S. Embassy in Nairobi for giving temporary asylum to Gibson
Kamau Kuria, an opposition leader.
   ---
   Died: John F. Connelly, 85, chairman of Crown Cork &amp; Seal
Co., Sunday, in Bryn Mawr, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900809-0050
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900809-0050.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
07/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GORBACHEV GAVE himself two years to improve the Soviet
Union's economy.
   On the third day of a Communist Party congress, the Soviet
president and party leader told a TV reporter, "I think that
in two years, if there are no changes, this leadership must
go." It was the first time he set a deadline for turning
around the country's economic and social problems. Contrary
to some expectations, the congress hasn't turned into an
all-out attack on Gorbachev, though both he and his Politburo
colleagues have taken sharp criticism. Instead, moderates and
hard-liners are engaged in a painful search for ways to
ensure the future existence of the party.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We need to retain socialism, but how?" asked one delegate
from the Ukraine. "Stalin built his model. Now we don't like
that, but we have no new model. We're in an ideological
crisis."
   ---
   Secretary of State Baker proposed that 24 Western nations
establish a Central American aid program to help "broaden the
support for democracy and development." Several countries
said they would consider the idea. The proposal came as the
two dozen countries agreed to offer aid to four Eastern
European nations.
   ---
   Albania's officials stated they would meet with a
representative of foreign embassies sheltering over 200
Albanian asylum-seekers in Tirana, the capital. In Vienna,
diplomats said embassies were told that people seeking to
leave would get passports. Mobs had stormed the embassies by
crashing trucks through gates or scaling walls.
   ---
   Iran's president said his nation had moved closer to peace
with Iraq over the past few months. Rafsanjani remarked that
he felt "the atmosphere between the two countries has
improved." On Tuesday, Iranian and Iraqi foreign ministers
held their first direct meeting since an August 1988
cease-fire that ended an eight-year war.
   ---
   Bush plans to propose, at a NATO summit opening today in
London, that Soviet leader Gorbachev be invited to address
the Western military alliance, according to diplomatic
sources. The U.S. also is recommending that Moscow and the
Warsaw Pact be allowed to send permanent observers to NATO
headquarters.
   ---
   Thatcher welcomed Mandela to London, three years after she
denounced the African National Congress as a terrorist
organization. The British prime minister and South African
black nationalist leader called their three-hour meeting a
success despite disagreement about economic sanctions and the
ANC's commitment to armed struggle.
   ---
   East Germany agreed to Bonn's agenda for political union
by proposing Dec. 2 for the first free vote in a united
Germany since 1932, preparing the way for talks to formally
end German division. West Germans viewed the accord as a sign
that East Berlin's leadership has overcome internal
opposition to swift unification.
   ---
   Studies found that aging men and cancer patients can
benefit from hormonal treatments. The increase in fat tissue
and muscular atrophy seen in many elderly men can be reversed
by injections of human growth hormone, one report said.
Another study concluded that a sex hormone helped cancer
patients gain weight.
   ---
   A government panel blamed the pilot for a USAir crash at
New York's LaGuardia Airport last Sept. 20 that killed two
passengers. The National Transportation Safety Board said the
captain failed to detect a rudder-control problem as he
taxied for takeoff, and then failed to correct the situation
aggressively.
   ---
   Liberia's president met with U.S. Ambassador Peter de Vos
in Monrovia as rebels tightened their grip on the capital.
Washington officials said Doe declined an offer for help in
fleeing the city, which has been without electricity and
water for over a week.
   ---
   The Energy Department estimates the cost of cleaning up
its nuclear-arms plants and other facilities soon could rise
to $6 billion a year -- about twice as much as the current
level. The department said it could cost $31.6 billion from
fiscal 1992 through fiscal 1996 to remove, treat and store
waste from nearly 100 sites.
   ---
   The New Jersey Supreme Court ordered two Princeton
University eating clubs to admit women as members. The
court's ruling came in an 11-year-old lawsuit filed by a
former Princeton student who claimed that the clubs'
males-only policies discriminated against women.
   ---
   A constitutional crisis was defused in Taiwan as the
ruling Nationalist Party government and opposition leaders
agreed on democratic changes, including a popular vote for
president to end four decades of one-party domination. Under
the accord, native Taiwanese will be given more political
power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
